<Content>A few quick words about the wonderful Island Shangri-La You can read all of the eloquent, detailed, journal entries about the Shangri-La, but I offer my few quick takeaways:Praises:-In-room technology (multifunction fax/printer, LCD in bathroom, wiring/lighting top notch, multiregion DVD player, power outlet strip which accepts many international plugs)-Amount of drawers for storage-Complete toiletry/sundry selection in the bathroom (laundry detergent included!)-Large in-room safe (fits my large laptop)-Maid service (your duvet is changed daily, ice is always refilled, turndown service great, complimentary in-room fruit daily, complimentary water bottles in-room daily)-Best laid-out hotel bathroom I've ever seen (separate tub, shower, tub, bidet, 2 sinks, plenty of shelving)-Plush interiors (the puffiest headboard I've ever seen)  great room art-First class gym and pool (you get an insulated bottled water at the outdoor pool)-Immaculate service EVERYWHERE - No one expects a tip (graciously accepted though)-Great china and glassware (wine glasses with flared rims, corkscrew, ice tongs, -Great location, adjoining the Pacific Place mall (great food court)Cons: (I really had to nitpick to come up with these)-The distance between the room's door knob (interior side) and the locking mechanism is only about 1.5 cm, so when you go to turn the doorknob, it can pinch your thumb.-The room's desk chair has wheels but it is difficult to roll around the room.-If you're watching TV from the desk, the sightline of the TV is partially obstructed by the cabinetry.-Pricey in-room internet access (600 HK/week or 120 HK/day)-Elevators can be warm on a hot day-In-room Nescafe instant coffee is weak (perhaps an improvement to the coffee filter bags would be in store?) 
