<Author>misdirected_baggage
<Content>Breathtaking I've stayed at this hotel on 3 separate occasions with consistent impressions. A Mercedes limo wisks you from the airport to the hotel while your registration is prepared at the hotel en-route (be forewarned, the limo ride is expensive and probably an option for the expense account traveler). The hotel's location is unsurpassed, with the peak tram and a Hong Kong park only steps away and the Pacific Place mall located almost directly below the hotel. Walking from the hotel to downtown, however, can be a bit tricky without instructions from the staff. Book a room on the harbor side of the hotel. Rooms start on the upper floors of the tower (lower floors are occupied by offices) and, although harbor-side rooms command a steep premium, the views are among the best in the world. Lying in bed watching the non-stop traffic in Hong Kong harbor may be among the most romantic and exotic things one can ever do. Bedside electronics control the curtains and lights. Though average sized, rooms are very well finished with large luxury marble baths including a bidet. The breakfast and lunch buffets are the culinary equivalent of shock and awe and may alone be worth the trip (reservations are necessary for lunch). Staff is helpful and efficient with reservations and directions. The main restaurant (Petrus) has excellent continental fare and a lovely view of the harbor and Kowloon. All in all, the Island Shangri-La is an oasis in the flurry of activity that characterizes Hong Kong. 
